<paragraph blockId="34.[264,1324,284,990]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Diagnosis. 
<bibRefCitation author="Burnham" box="[454,660,284,310]" pageId="34" pageNumber="67" refString="Burnham, L. (1983) Studies on Upper Carboniferous insects: 1. The Geraridae (Order Protorthoptera). Psyche, 90, 1 - 57." type="journal article" year="1983">
Burnham (
<number box="[590,651,284,310]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="1983.0">1983</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
compared 
<taxonomicName box="[810,908,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Geraridae" genus="Gerarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Geraroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[810,908,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Gerarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<emphasis box="[966,1098,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Nacekomia</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[1123,1316,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Progenentomum</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[264,420,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Genentomum</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[483,604,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Gerarulus</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Kukalova-Peck" box="[622,1084,324,350]" pageId="34" pageNumber="69" refString="Kukalova-Peck, J. &amp; Brauckmann, C. (1992). Most Paleozoic Protorthoptera are ancestral hemipteroids: major wing braces as clues to a new phylogeny of Neoptera (Insecta). Canadian Journal of Zoology, 70, 2452 - 2473." type="journal article" year="1992">
Kukalová­Peck &amp; Brauckmann (
<number box="[1014,1075,324,350]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="1992.0">1992</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
did not give a new diagnosis of the genus. Thus we propose a new diagnosis, based on forewings characters: ScP long, straight, anteriorly pectinate; branches of ScP simple or shortly ramified; 
<collectingCountry box="[1287,1323,404,430]" name="Poland" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">RP</collectingCountry>
with few distal branches; MA differentiated into MA 
<number box="[960,969,444,470]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="1.0">1</number>
and MA 
<number box="[1098,1112,444,470]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="2.0">2</number>
; MA 
<number box="[1187,1196,444,470]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="1.0">1</number>
generally connected to 
<collectingCountry box="[429,465,484,510]" name="Poland" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">RP</collectingCountry>
by a short cross­vein or shortly fused; MP ramified very proximally; CuPa present, more or less weak; CuPb ramified with an anterior branch long or reduced, and either connected or not to CuPa.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[264,1324,284,990]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Note. The very long, spiny pronotum of numerous 
<taxonomicName box="[998,1096,604,629]" class="Insecta" family="Geraridae" genus="Gerarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Geraroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[998,1096,604,629]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Gerarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. is a strong synapomorphy (
<bibRefCitation author="Burnham" box="[455,637,644,670]" pageId="34" pageNumber="67" refString="Burnham, L. (1983) Studies on Upper Carboniferous insects: 1. The Geraridae (Order Protorthoptera). Psyche, 90, 1 - 57." type="journal article" year="1983">
Burnham 
<number box="[575,637,644,670]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="1983.0">1983</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kukalova-Peck" box="[650,1091,644,670]" pageId="34" pageNumber="69" refString="Kukalova-Peck, J. &amp; Brauckmann, C. (1992). Most Paleozoic Protorthoptera are ancestral hemipteroids: major wing braces as clues to a new phylogeny of Neoptera (Insecta). Canadian Journal of Zoology, 70, 2452 - 2473." type="journal article" year="1992">
Kukalová­Peck &amp; Brauckmann 
<number box="[1031,1091,644,670]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="1992.0">1992</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) but is unknown in 
<taxonomicName box="[264,442,684,709]" class="Insecta" family="Geraridae" genus="Gerarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Geraroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bruesi">
<emphasis box="[264,442,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Gerarus bruesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, thus it is not possible to determine if it is at the family or genus level.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[264,1324,284,990]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Discussion. 
<taxonomicName box="[457,625,724,749]" class="Insecta" family="Geraridae" genus="Gerarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Geraroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vetus">
<emphasis box="[457,625,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Gerarus vetus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as figured by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kukalova-Peck" pageId="34" pageNumber="69" refString="Kukalova-Peck, J. &amp; Brauckmann, C. (1992). Most Paleozoic Protorthoptera are ancestral hemipteroids: major wing braces as clues to a new phylogeny of Neoptera (Insecta). Canadian Journal of Zoology, 70, 2452 - 2473." type="journal article" year="1992">
Kukalová­Peck &amp; Brauckmann (
<number box="[1194,1258,724,750]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="1992.0">1992</number>
: figs. 4,10,13)
</bibRefCitation>
has a simple MP, suggesting closer relationships with 
<taxonomicName box="[1033,1160,764,790]" class="Insecta" family="Acrididae;Dericorythidae;Lathiceridae;Lentulidae;Lithidiidae;Ommexechidae;Pamphagidae;Pamphagodidae;Pyrgacrididae;Romaleidae;Tristiridae;Dzhajloutshellidae;Elcanidae;Permelcanidae;Chorotypidae;Episactidae;Eumastacidae;Euschmidtiidae;Mastacideidae;Morabidae;Promastacidae;Thericleidae;Gryllavidae;Baissogryllidae;Gryllidae;Mogoplistidae;Phalangopsidae;Protogryllidae;Trigonidiidae;Gryllotalpidae;Myrmecophilidae;Eospilopteronidae;Haglidae;Hagloedischiidae;Prezottophlebiidae;Prophalangopsidae;Tuphellidae;Bouretidae;Eolocustopsidae;Locustavidae;Locustopsidae;Anelcanidae;Bintoniellidae;Mesoedischiidae;Oedischiidae;Proparagryllacrididae;Pruvostitidae;Paratitanidae;Permoraphidiidae;Pseudelcanidae;Thueringoedischiidae;Phasmomimidae;Pneumoridae;Proscopiidae;Pyrgomorphidae;Raphoglidae;Regiatidae;Rhaphidophoridae;Schizodactylidae;Anostostomatidae;Cooloolidae;Gryllacrididae;Stenopelmatidae;Tanaoceridae;Mesotitanidae;Tcholmanvissiidae;Tetrigidae;Haglotettigoniidae;Tettigoniidae;Tettoedischiidae;Adumbratomorphidae;Triassomantidae;Cylindrachetidae;Ripipterygidae;Tridactylidae;Trigonopterygidae;Xyronotidae;Vitimiidae;Xenopteridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Orthoptera</taxonomicName>
than with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Geraridae" genus="Gerarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Geraroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bruesi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">G. bruesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[397,527,804,829]" class="Insecta" family="Geraridae" genus="Gerarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Geraroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="danielsi">
<emphasis box="[397,527,804,829]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">G. danielsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which have an MP which is clearly and very proximally ramified. In his composite reconstruction of the 
<typeStatus box="[713,816,844,870]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Burnham" authorityName="Burnham" box="[854,1072,844,870]" class="Insecta" family="Geraridae" genus="Gerarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Geraroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vetus">
<emphasis box="[854,949,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">G. vetus</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Burnham" box="[963,1072,844,870]" pageId="34" pageNumber="67" refString="Burnham, L. (1983) Studies on Upper Carboniferous insects: 1. The Geraridae (Order Protorthoptera). Psyche, 90, 1 - 57." type="journal article" year="1983">Burnham</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<number box="[1088,1152,844,870]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="1983.0">1983</number>
: fig. 
<number box="[1209,1225,844,870]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="4.0">4</number>
) did not figure a simple but a forked MP vein. It is not certain if the 
<typeStatus box="[983,1085,884,910]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[1129,1226,884,909]" class="Insecta" family="Geraridae" genus="Gerarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Geraroptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vetus">
<emphasis box="[1129,1226,884,909]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">G. vetus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the specimens studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kukalova-Peck" box="[521,973,924,950]" pageId="34" pageNumber="69" refString="Kukalova-Peck, J. &amp; Brauckmann, C. (1992). Most Paleozoic Protorthoptera are ancestral hemipteroids: major wing braces as clues to a new phylogeny of Neoptera (Insecta). Canadian Journal of Zoology, 70, 2452 - 2473." type="journal article" year="1992">
Kukalová­Peck &amp; Brauckmann (
<number box="[904,965,924,950]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" value="1992.0">1992</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
belong to the same species or even genus. Thus, the monophyly of this genus remains unclear.
</paragraph>
